# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gantt-charts-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] It is also a part of the discipline of history including earth history, the earth sciences, and study of the geologic time scale.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Chronology is the science of locating historical events in time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] It relies mostly upon chronometry, which is also known as timekeeping, and historiography, which examines the writing of history and the use of historical methods.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Radiocarbon dating estimates the age of formerly living things by measuring the proportion of carbon-14 isotope in their carbon content.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Dendrochronology estimates the age of trees by correlation of the various growth rings in their wood to known year-by-year reference sequences in the region to reflect year-to-year climatic variation.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Dendrochronology is used in turn as a calibration reference for radiocarbon dating curves.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] The familiar terms *calendar* and *era* (within the meaning of a coherent system of numbered calendar years) concern two complementary fundamental concepts of chronology.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] For example, during eight centuries the calendar belonging to the Christian era, which era was taken in use in the 8th century by Bede, was the Julian calendar, but after the year 1582 it was the Gregorian calendar.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Dionysius Exiguus (about the year 500) was the founder of that era, which is nowadays the most widespread dating system on earth.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] An epoch is the date (year usually) when an era begins.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] It was used systematically for the first time only about the year 400, by the Iberian historian Orosius.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Pope Boniface IV, in about the year 600, seems to have been the first who made a connection between this era and Anno Domini.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Dionysius Exiguus' Anno Domini era (which contains only calendar years *AD*) was extended by Bede to the complete Christian era (which contains, in addition all calendar years *BC*, but no *year zero*).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] While of critical importance to the historian, methods of determining chronology are used in most disciplines of science, especially astronomy, geology, paleontology and archaeology.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] In the absence of written history, with its chronicles and king lists, late 19th century archaeologists found that they could develop relative chronologies based on pottery techniques and styles.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] In the field of Egyptology, William Flinders Petrie pioneered sequence dating to penetrate pre-dynastic Neolithic times, using groups of contemporary artefacts deposited together at a single time in graves and working backwards methodically from the earliest historical phases of Egypt.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] This method of dating is known as seriation.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Known wares discovered at strata in sometimes quite distant sites, the product of trade, helped extend the network of chronologies.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Some cultures have retained the name applied to them in reference to characteristic forms, for lack of an idea of what they called themselves: "The Beaker People" in northern Europe during the 3rd millennium BCE, for example.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Laboratory techniques developed particularly after mid-20th century helped constantly revise and refine the chronologies developed for specific cultural areas.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Unrelated dating methods help reinforce a chronology, an axiom of corroborative evidence.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Ideally, archaeological materials used for dating a site should complement each other and provide a means of cross-checking.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Conclusions drawn from just one unsupported technique are usually regarded as unreliable.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] The fundamental problem of chronology is to synchronize events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] By synchronizing an event it becomes possible to relate it to the current time and to compare the event to other events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Among historians, a typical need is to synchronize the reigns of kings and leaders in order to relate the history of one country or region to that of another.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] For example, the Chronicon of Eusebius (325 A.D.) is one of the major works of historical synchronism.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] The first contains narrative chronicles of nine different kingdoms: Chaldean, Assyrian, Median, Lydian, Persian, Hebrew, Greek, Peloponnesian, Asian, and Roman.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] The second part is a long table synchronizing the events from each of the nine kingdoms in parallel columns.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] By comparing the parallel columns, the reader can determine which events were contemporaneous, or how many years separated two different events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] To place all the events on the same time scale, Eusebius used an Anno Mundi (A.M.) era, meaning that events were dated from the supposed beginning of the world as computed from the Book of Genesis in the Hebrew Pentateuch.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] According to the computation Eusebius used, this occurred in 5199 B.C.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] The Chronicon of Eusebius was widely used in the medieval world to establish the dates and times of historical events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Subsequent chronographers, such as George Syncellus (died circa 811), analyzed and elaborated on the Chronicon by comparing with other chronologies.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] The last great chronographer was Joseph Justus Scaliger (1540-1609) who reconstructed the lost Chronicon and synchronized all of ancient history in his two major works, *De emendatione temporum* (1583) and *Thesaurus temporum* (1606).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Much of modern historical datings and chronology of the ancient world ultimately derives from these two works.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Scaliger invented the concept of the Julian Day which is still used as the standard unified scale of time for both historians and astronomers.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] In addition to the literary methods of synchronism used by traditional chronographers such as Eusebius, Syncellus and Scaliger, it is possible to synchronize events by archaeological or astronomical means.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] For example, the Eclipse of Thales, described in the first book of Herodotus can potentially be used to date the Lydian War because the eclipse took place during the middle of an important battle in that war.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Likewise, various eclipses and other astronomical events described in ancient records can be used to astronomically synchronize historical events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/chronology] Another method to synchronize events is the use of archaeological findings, such as pottery, to do sequence dating.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] In mathematics, and more specifically in graph theory, a **directed graph** (or **digraph**) is a graph that is made up of a set of vertices connected by directed edges, often called **arcs**.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] It differs from an ordinary or undirected graph, in that the latter is defined in terms of unordered pairs of vertices, which are usually called *edges*, *links* or *lines*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The aforementioned definition does not allow a directed graph to have multiple arrows with the same source and target nodes, but some authors consider a broader definition that allows directed graphs to have such multiple arcs (namely, they allow the arc set to be a multiset).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] Sometimes these entities are called **directed multigraphs** (or **multidigraphs**).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] On the other hand, the aforementioned definition allows a directed graph to have loops (that is, arcs that directly connect nodes with themselves), but some authors consider a narrower definition that does not allow directed graphs to have loops.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] Directed graphs without loops may be called **simple directed graphs**, while directed graphs with loops may be called *loop-digraphs* (see section Types of directed graph).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] An arc (*x*, *y*) is considered to be directed *from* *x* *to* *y*; *y* is called the *head* and *x* is called the *tail* of the arc; *y* is said to be a *direct successor* of *x* and *x* is said to be a *direct predecessor* of *y*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] If a path leads from *x* to *y*, then *y* is said to be a *successor* of *x* and *reachable* from *x*, and *x* is said to be a *predecessor* of *y*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The arc (*y*, *x*) is called the *reversed arc* of (*x*, *y*).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a multidigraph with loops is the integer-valued matrix with rows and columns corresponding to the vertices, where a nondiagonal entry *a**ij* is the number of arcs from vertex *i* to vertex *j*, and the diagonal entry *a**ii* is the number of loops at vertex *i*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph is a logical matrix, and is unique up to permutation of rows and columns.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] Another matrix representation for a directed graph is its incidence matrix.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] For a vertex, the number of head ends adjacent to a vertex is called the *indegree* of the vertex and the number of tail ends adjacent to a vertex is its *outdegree* (called *branching factor* in trees).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The indegree of *v* is denoted deg−(*v*) and its outdegree is denoted deg+(*v*).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] A vertex with deg−(*v*) = 0 is called a *source*, as it is the origin of each of its outgoing arcs.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] Similarly, a vertex with deg+(*v*) = 0 is called a *sink*, since it is the end of each of its incoming arcs.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] If for every vertex *v* ∈ *V*, deg+(*v*) = deg−(*v*), the graph is called a *balanced directed graph*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The degree sequence of a directed graph is the list of its indegree and outdegree pairs; for the above example we have degree sequence ((2, 0), (2, 2), (0, 2), (1, 1)).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The degree sequence is a directed graph invariant so isomorphic directed graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a directed graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic digraphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The directed graph realization problem is the problem of finding a directed graph with the degree sequence a given sequence of positive integer pairs.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] This problem can either be solved by the Kleitman–Wang algorithm or by the Fulkerson–Chen–Anstee theorem.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] A directed graph is *weakly connected* (or just *connected*) if the undirected *underlying graph* obtained by replacing all directed edges of the graph with undirected edges is a connected graph.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] A directed graph is *strongly connected* or *strong* if it contains a directed path from *x* to *y* (and from *y* to *x*) for every pair of vertices (*x*, *y*).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] The *strong components* are the maximal strongly connected subgraphs.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/directed-graph] A connected rooted graph (or *flow graph*) is one where there exists a directed path to every vertex from a distinguished *root vertex*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] A **Gantt chart** is a bar chart that illustrates a project schedule.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] It was designed and popularized by Henry Gantt c.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Modern Gantt charts also show the dependency relationships between activities and the current schedule status.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] A Gantt chart is a type of bar chart that illustrates a project schedule.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] This chart lists the tasks to be performed on the vertical axis, and time intervals on the horizontal axis.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] The width of the horizontal bars in the graph shows the duration of each activity.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts illustrate the start and finish dates of the terminal elements and summary elements of a project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Terminal elements and summary elements constitute the work breakdown structure of the project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Modern Gantt charts also show the dependency (i.e., precedence network) relationships between activities.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts can be used to show current schedule status using percent-complete shadings and a vertical "TODAY" line.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts are sometimes equated with bar charts.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts are usually created initially using an *early start time approach*, where each task is scheduled to start immediately when its prerequisites are complete.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] This method maximizes the float time available for all tasks.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Widely used in project planning in the present day, Gantt charts were considered revolutionary when introduced.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] The first known tool of this type was developed in 1896 by Karol Adamiecki, who called it a *harmonogram*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Adamiecki, however, published his chart only in Russian and Polish which limited both its adoption and recognition of his authorship.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] In 1912, Hermann Schürch published what could be considered Gantt charts while discussing a construction project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Charts of the type published by Schürch appear to have been in common use in Germany at the time; however, the prior development leading to Schürch's work is unclear.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Unlike later Gantt charts, Schürch's charts did not display interdependencies, leaving them to be inferred by the reader.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] These were also static representations of a planned schedule.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] The chart is named after Henry Gantt (1861–1919), who designed his chart around the years 1910–1915.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt originally created his tool for systematic, routine operations.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] He designed this visualization tool to more easily measure productivity levels of employees and gauge which employees were under- or over-performing.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt also frequently included graphics and other visual indicators in his charts to track performance.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] One of the first major applications of Gantt charts was by the United States during World War I, at the instigation of General William Crozier.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] The earliest Gantt charts were drawn on paper and therefore had to be redrawn entirely in order to adjust to schedule changes.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] For many years, project managers used pieces of paper or blocks for Gantt chart bars so they could be adjusted as needed.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt's collaborator Walter Polakov introduced Gantt charts to the Soviet Union in 1929 when he was working for the Supreme Soviet of the National Economy.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] They were used in developing the First Five Year Plan, supplying Russian translations to explain their use.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] In the 1980s, personal computers allowed widespread creation of complex and elaborate Gantt charts.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] The first desktop applications were intended mainly for project managers and project schedulers.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] With the advent of the Internet and increased collaboration over networks at the end of the 1990s, Gantt charts became a common feature of web-based applications, including collaborative groupware..
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] By 2012, almost all Gantt charts were made by software which can easily adjust to schedule changes.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] In 1999, Gantt charts were identified as "one of the most widely used management tools for project scheduling and control".
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] In the following tables there are seven tasks, labeled *a* through *g*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Some tasks can be done concurrently (*a* and *b*) while others cannot be done until their predecessor task is complete (*c* and *d* cannot begin until *a* is complete).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Additionally, each task has three time estimates: the optimistic time estimate (*O*), the most likely or normal time estimate (*M*), and the pessimistic time estimate (*P*).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] The expected time (*TE*) is estimated using the beta probability distribution for the time estimates, using the formula (*O* + 4*M* + *P*) ÷ 6.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Once this step is complete, one can draw a Gantt chart or a network diagram.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] In a progress Gantt chart, tasks are shaded in proportion to the degree of their completion: a task that is 60% complete would be 60% shaded, starting from the left.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] A vertical line is drawn at the time index when the progress Gantt chart is created, and this line can then be compared with shaded tasks.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] If everything is on schedule, all task portions left of the line will be shaded, and all task portions right of the line will not be shaded.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] This provides a visual representation of how the project and its tasks are ahead or behind schedule.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Linked Gantt charts contain lines indicating the dependencies between tasks.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] However, linked Gantt charts quickly become cluttered in all but the simplest cases.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Critical path network diagrams are superior to visually communicate the relationships between tasks.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Nevertheless, Gantt charts are often preferred over network diagrams because Gantt charts are easily interpreted without training, whereas critical path diagrams require training to interpret.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt chart software typically provides mechanisms to link task dependencies, although this data may or may not be visually represented.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] Gantt charts and network diagrams are often used for the same project, both being generated from the same data by a software application.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] The Gantt chart's widespread adoption is perhaps less based on its universal application and suitability as perhaps the absence of any alternative.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/gantt-chart] It flattens assumptions, which in turn can constrain the ability to respond to uncertainty and change.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The **program** **evaluation and review technique** (**PERT**) is a statistical tool used in project management, which was designed to analyze and represent the tasks involved in completing a given project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] PERT was originally developed by Charles E.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Clark for the United States Navy in 1958; it is commonly used in conjunction with the Critical Path Method (CPM), which was also introduced in 1958.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] PERT is a method of analyzing the tasks involved in completing a project, especially the time needed to complete each task, and to identify the minimum time needed to complete the total project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] It incorporates uncertainty by making it possible to schedule a project while not knowing precisely the details and durations of all the activities.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] It is more event-oriented than start- and completion-oriented, and is used more for projects where time is the major constraint rather than cost.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] It is applied to very large-scale, one-time, complex, non-routine infrastructure projects, as well as R&D projects.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] PERT and CPM are complementary tools, because "CPM employs one time estimation and one cost estimation for each activity; PERT may utilize three time estimates (optimistic, expected, and pessimistic) and no costs for each activity.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] PERT was developed primarily to simplify the planning and scheduling of large and complex projects.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] It was developed by the United States Navy Special Projects Office, Lockheed Aircraft, and Booz Allen Hamilton to support the Navy's Polaris missile project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] It found applications throughout industry.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] An early example is the 1968 Winter Olympics in Grenoble which used PERT from 1965 until the opening of the 1968 Games.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] This project model was the first of its kind, a revival for the scientific management of Frederick Taylor and later refined by Henry Ford (Fordism).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] DuPont's CPM was invented at roughly the same time as PERT.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Initially PERT stood for *Program Evaluation Research Task,* but by 1959 was renamed.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] It had been made public in 1958 in two publications of the U.S.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Department of the Navy, entitled *Program Evaluation Research Task, Summary Report, Phase 1.* and *Phase 2.* both primarily written by Charles F.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] In a 1959 article in *The American Statistician*, Willard Fazar, Head of the Program Evaluation Branch, Special Projects Office, U.S.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Navy, gave a detailed description of the main concepts of PERT.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Ten years after the introduction of PERT, the American librarian Maribeth Brennan compiled a selected bibliography with about 150 publications on PERT and CPM, all published between 1958 and 1968.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] For the subdivision of work units in PERT another tool was developed: the Work Breakdown Structure.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] In a PERT diagram, the main building block is the *event*, with connections to its known predecessor events and successor events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The first step for scheduling the project is to determine the tasks that the project requires and the order in which they must be completed.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The order may be easy to record for some tasks (e.g., when building a house, the land must be graded before the foundation can be laid) while difficult for others (there are two areas that need to be graded, but there are only enough bulldozers to do one).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Additionally, the time estimates usually reflect the normal, non-rushed time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Many times, the time required to execute the task can be reduced for an additional cost or a reduction in the quality.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] In the following example there are seven tasks, labeled *A* through *G*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Some tasks can be done concurrently (*A* and *B*) while others cannot be done until their predecessor task is complete (*C* cannot begin until *A* is complete).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The expected time (*te*) is computed using the formula (*o* + 4*m* + *p*) ÷ 6.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] A network diagram can be created by hand or by using diagram software.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] There are two types of network diagrams, activity on arrow (AOA) and activity on node (AON).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Activity on node diagrams are generally easier to create and interpret.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] To create an AON diagram, it is recommended (but not required) to start with a node named *start*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] This "activity" has a duration of zero (0).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Then you draw each activity that does not have a predecessor activity (*a* and *b* in this example) and connect them with an arrow from start to each node.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Next, since both *c* and *d* list *a* as a predecessor activity, their nodes are drawn with arrows coming from *a*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Activity *e* is listed with *b* and *c* as predecessor activities, so node *e* is drawn with arrows coming from both *b* and *c*, signifying that *e* cannot begin until both *b* and *c* have been completed.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Activity *f* has *d* as a predecessor activity, so an arrow is drawn connecting the activities.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Likewise, an arrow is drawn from *e* to *g*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Since there are no activities that come after *f* or *g*, it is recommended (but again not required) to connect them to a node labeled *finish*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] A node like this one can be used to display the activity name, duration, ES, EF, LS, LF, and slack.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] By itself, the network diagram pictured above does not give much more information than a Gantt chart; however, it can be expanded to display more information.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] In order to determine this information it is assumed that the activities and normal duration times are given.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The first step is to determine the ES and EF.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The ES is defined as the maximum EF of all predecessor activities, unless the activity in question is the first activity, for which the ES is zero (0).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The EF is the ES plus the task duration (EF = ES + duration).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Barring any unforeseen events, the project should take 19.51 work days to complete.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The next step is to determine the late start (LS) and late finish (LF) of each activity.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] This will eventually show if there are activities that have slack.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The LF is defined as the minimum LS of all successor activities, unless the activity is the last activity, for which the LF equals the EF.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The LS is the LF minus the task duration (LS = LF − duration).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The next step is to determine the critical path and if any activities have slack.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The critical path is the path that takes the **longest** to complete.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] To determine the path times, add the task durations for all available paths.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Activities that have slack can be delayed without changing the overall time of the project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Slack is computed in one of two ways, slack = LF − EF *or* slack = LS − ES.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Activities that are on the critical path have a slack of zero (0).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The critical path is *aceg* and the critical time is 19.51 work days.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] There can be more than one critical path (in a project more complex than this example) or that the critical path can change.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] For example, let's say that activities *d* and *f* take their pessimistic (b) times to complete instead of their expected (TE) times.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The critical path is now *adf* and the critical time is 22 work days.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] On the other hand, if activity *c* can be reduced to one work day, the path time for *aceg* is reduced to 15.34 work days, which is slightly less than the time of the new critical path, *beg* (15.67 work days).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Assuming these scenarios do not happen, the slack for each activity can now be determined.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Therefore, activity *b* can be delayed almost 4 work days without delaying the project.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Likewise, activity *d* **or** activity *f* can be delayed 4.68 work days without delaying the project (alternatively, *d* and *f* can be delayed 2.34 work days each).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Depending upon the capabilities of the data input phase of the critical path algorithm, it may be possible to create a loop, such as A -> B -> C -> A.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] This can cause simple algorithms to loop indefinitely.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] Although it is possible to "mark" nodes that have been visited, then clear the "marks" upon completion of the process, a far simpler mechanism involves computing the total of all activity durations.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] If an EF of more than the total is found, the computation should be terminated.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] It is worth saving the identities of the most recently visited dozen or so nodes to help identify the problem link.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] During project execution a real-life project will never execute exactly as it was planned due to uncertainty.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] This can be due to ambiguity resulting from subjective estimates that are prone to human errors or can be the result of variability arising from unexpected events or risks.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] The main reason that PERT may provide inaccurate information about the project completion time is due to this schedule uncertainty.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] This inaccuracy may be large enough to render such estimates as not helpful.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] One possible method to maximize solution robustness is to include safety in the baseline schedule in order to absorb disruptions.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] This is called *proactive scheduling*, however, allowing for every possible disruption would be very slow and couldn't be accommodated by the baseline schedule.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/program-evaluation-and-review-technique] A second approach, termed *reactive scheduling*, defines a procedure to react to disruptions that cannot be absorbed by the baseline schedule.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] A **timeline** is a list of events displayed in chronological order.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] It is typically a graphic design showing a long bar labelled with dates paralleling it, and usually contemporaneous events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Timelines can use any suitable scale representing time, suiting the subject and data; many use a linear scale, in which a unit of distance is equal to a set amount of time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] This timescale is dependent on the events in the timeline.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] A timeline of evolution can be over millions of years, whereas a timeline for the day of the September 11 attacks can take place over minutes, and that of an explosion over milliseconds.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] While many timelines use a linear timescale—especially where very large or small timespans are relevant -- logarithmic timelines entail a logarithmic scale of time; some "hurry up and wait" chronologies are depicted with zoom lens metaphors.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] More usually, "timeline" refers merely to a data set which could be displayed as described above.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Time and space are variously intertwined concepts.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] The line is ubiquitous in clocks in the form of a circle, time is spoken of in terms of length, intervals, a before and an after.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] The idea of orderly, segmented time is also represented in almanacs, calendars, charts, graphs, genealogical and evolutionary trees, where the line is central.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Originally, chronological events were arranged in a mostly textual form.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] This took form in annals, like king lists.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Alongside them, the table was used like in the Greek tables of Olympiads and Roman lists of consuls and triumphs.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Annals had little narrative and noted what happened to people, making no distinction between natural and human actions.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] In Europe, from the 4th century, the dominant chronological notation was the table.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] This can be partially credited to Eusebius, who laid out the relations between Jewish, pagan, and Christian histories in parallel columns, culminating in the Roman Empire, according to the Christian view when Christ was born to spread salvation as far as possible.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] His work was widely copied and was among the first printed books.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] This served the idea of Christian world history and providential time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] The table is easy to produce, append, and read with indices, so it also fit the Renaissance scholars' absorption of a wide variety of sources with its focus on commonalities.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] These uses made the table with years in one column and places of events (kingdoms) on the top the dominant visual structure of time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] By the 17th century, chronology and geography became the two sources of precise information for European early modern historians.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] In geography, Renaissance mapmakers updated Ptolemy's maps and the map became a symbol of the power of monarchs, and knowledge.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Likewise, the idea that a singular chronology of world history from contemporary sources is possible affected historians.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] The want for precision in chronology gave rise to historical eclipses in tables, like in the case of Gerardus Mercator.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Various graphical experiments emerged, from fitting the whole of history on a calendar year to series of historical drawings, in the hopes of making a metaphorical map of time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Developments in printing and engraving that made practical larger and more detailed book illustrations allowed these changes, but in the 17th century, the table with some modifications continued to dominate.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] The modern timeline emerged in Joseph Priestley's *A Chart of Biography*, published in 1765.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] It presented dates simply and provided an analogue for the concept of historical progress that was becoming popular in the 18th century.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] However, as Priestley recognized, history is not totally linear.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] The table has the advantage in that it can present many of these intersections and branching paths.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] For Priestley, its main use was a "mechanical help to the knowledge of history", not as an image of history.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Regardless, the timeline had become very popular during the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Positivism emerged in the 19th century and the development of chronophotography and tree ring analysis made visible time taking place at various speeds.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] This encouraged people to think that events might be truly objectively recorded.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] However, in some cases, filling in a timeline with more data only pushed it towards impracticality.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Jacques Barbeu-Duborg's 1753 *Chronologie Universelle* was mounted on a 54-feet-long (16½ m) scroll.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Charles Joseph Minard's 1869 thematic map of casualties of the French army in its Russian campaign put much less focus on the one-directional line.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Charles Renouvier's 1876 *Uchronie*, a branching map of the history of Europe, depicted both the actual course of history and counterfactual paths.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] At the end of the 19th century, Henri Bergson declared the metaphor of the timeline to be deceiving in *Time and Free Will*.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] The question of big history and deep time engendered estranging forms of the timeline, like in Olaf Stapledon's 1930 work *Last and First Men* where timelines are drawn on scales from the historical to the cosmological.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Similar techniques are used by the Long Now Foundation, and the difficulties of chronological representation have been presented by visual artists including Francis Picabia, On Kawara, J.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] There are many methods to visualize timelines.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Historically, timelines were static images and were generally drawn or printed on paper.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Timelines relied heavily on graphic design, and the ability of the artist to visualize the data.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Timelines are often used in education to help students and researchers with understanding the order or chronology of historical events and trends for a subject.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] To show time on a specific scale on an axis, a timeline can visualize time lapses between events, durations (such as lifetimes or wars), and the simultaneity or the overlap of spans and events.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Timelines are particularly useful for studying history, as they convey a sense of change over time.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Wars and social movements are often shown as timelines.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Timelines are also useful for biographies.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Another type of timeline is used for project management.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Timelines help team members know what milestones need to be achieved and under what time schedule.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] An example is establishing a project timeline in the implementation phase of the life cycle of a computer system.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Timelines (no longer constrained by previous space and functional limitations) are now digital and interactive, generally created with computer software.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] Microsoft Encarta encyclopedia provided one of the earliest multimedia timelines intended for students and the general public.
[src:gantt-charts-viz/timeline] ChronoZoom is another example of interactive timeline software.
